<http://w3id.org/opino/> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Ontology> .
<http://w3id.org/opino/> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#versionIRI> <http://w3id.org/opino/0.1.0> .
<http://w3id.org/opino/> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#imports> <http://purl.org/emmedi/hico/2020-03-31> .
<http://w3id.org/opino/> <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/creator> "Andrea Schimmenti"@en .
<http://w3id.org/opino/> <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/date> "2026-04-30T14:30:00"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> .
<http://w3id.org/opino/> <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/description> "OPINO (OPINion ONtology) is an ontology for the formal \nrepresentation of opinions as Knowledge Graphs, grounded in \nthe Description and Situation (DnS) Ontology Design Pattern (Gangemi and \nMika 2003) and the DOLCE+DnS Ultralite foundational ontology (DUL). \n\nOPINO adopts DnS as its core architectural backbone. Its primary purpose \nis to serve as a domain-agnostic interface for representing opinions \nacross heterogeneous contexts, without committing to a specific \nrepresentational paradigm. In this context, an opinion is understood as \na perspective-dependent description of an entity, premised on a construed \nstate of affairs. Representations built with OPINO can be aligned to or \nconverted into other models depending on the requirements of a given \napplication. For instance, in the context of projects leveraging CRMinf \nas the primary model for representing propositional content, OPINO can \nwork as a neutral interface layer that bridges the opinion's epistemic \nstructure with CRMinf's inference and belief machinery. Similarly, OPINO \nrepresentations can be mapped to Digital Hermeneutics or \nnanopublication-based architectures when layered provenance is required.\n\nThe core class of OPINO is opino:Opinion, a subclass of dul:Description \nthat represents a perspective-dependent description of an entity, \npremised on a construed state of affairs. The entity being described \n(via opino:describes) and the state of affairs that grounds the \ndescription (via opino:isPremisedOn) are distinct: the Opinion is a \nclaim about an entity that results from the cognizer's construal of \nobservable or documented facts. For instance, the opinion 'the Donation \nof Constantine is a forgery' describes the Donation of Constantine, and \nis premised on a Construal involving the presence of anachronistic Latin, \nfeudal terminology, and inconsistent dating formulae — facts perceived \nand interpreted by the cognizer as evidence for the claim. A different \ncognizer may construe the same facts differently, or construe different \nfacts entirely, producing a different Opinion about the same entity.\n\nAn Opinion is not necessarily an interpretation in the hermeneutical \nsense. It may be as simple as 'Marco is good' or 'this painting is \nbeautiful'. What distinguishes it from a neutral assertion of fact is \nits perspective-dependence: it is always the description of an entity \nas seen through the lens of a specific cognizer, grounded in what that \ncognizer perceives. The opino:Interpretation subclass is reserved for \nthe specific case where an Opinion results from a deliberate \nhermeneutical interpretive act — formally represented as a \nhico:InterpretationAct in HiCO — involving a documented methodology, \na set of criteria, and a source. An Interpretation inherits all the \nepistemic properties of Opinion while adding the full provenance layer \nprovided by HiCO. Not every Opinion is an Interpretation: opinions \nformed in everyday discourse, automated extraction pipelines, or \ncollective community processes may be generated by plain prov:Activity \ninstances without the hermeneutical apparatus that HiCO models.\n\nAn Opinion is satisfied by a Construal — a perspective-dependent \ndul:Situation that reifies the set of facts as perceived by the \ncognizer, following the notion of construal from cognitive linguistics \nand social psychology (Ross 1987; Langacker 2008). The Construal is \nvalid only when interpreted from the standpoint of a specific agent: \nthe same objective state of affairs may be construed differently by \ndifferent cognizers, leading to different Opinions over the same \nentities. The Opinion is the description that emerges from the analysis \nof a Construal — it is what the cognizer concludes from what they \nperceive, directed at the entity the claim is about.\n\nEach Opinion carries an epistemic status, represented by an \nEpistemicStatusParameter valued by one of three EpistemicRegion \nindividuals: AssertionValue (the holder commits to the claim as their \ncurrent considered interpretation), HypothesisValue (the holder commits \ntentatively, pending further evidence), or ConjectureValue (the holder \nentertains the claim as a possibility without sufficient evidence to \nassert it). This determines whether an Opinion is classified as an \nopino:Assertion, opino:Hypothesis, or opino:Conjecture respectively, \nvia owl:equivalentClass definitions.\n\nEach Opinion is also tied to the provenance of its production via \nprov:wasGeneratedBy, which relates it to a prov:Activity. When the \ngenerating activity is a hico:InterpretationAct — as defined by the \nHistorical Context Ontology (HiCO; Daquino and Tomasi 2015) — the \nOpinion is equivalent to an opino:Interpretation. HiCO provides the \nfull provenance context of the interpretive act: the agent who performed \nit, the time, the methodology, and the source document. OPINO does not \nreplicate this layer but bridges to it via the provenance relation.\n\nAgreement, disagreement, and support between Opinions are deliberately \nkept outside the OPINO model. These dynamics are social and \ncommunity-level epistemic phenomena, appropriately handled at the level \nof the prov:Activity node using CiTO properties (cito:agreesWith, \ncito:disagreesWith, cito:citesAsEvidence) as already provided by HiCO's \nintegration with CiTO. OPINO focuses exclusively on the epistemic \nstructure of the individual claim.\n\nThe properties of an Opinion are:\n- opino:isPremisedOn — relates an Opinion to the Construal that \n  constitutes its premises (subproperty of dul:isSatisfiedBy)\n- opino:hasEpistemicStatus — relates an Opinion to its \n  EpistemicStatusParameter (Functional; subproperty of dul:hasParameter)\n- opino:heldBy — shortcut relating an Opinion directly to its holder \n  (range: owl:Thing; subproperty of dul:associatedWith)\n- opino:describes — relates an Opinion to the entity its propositional \n  content is about (subproperty of dul:describes)\n- opino:usesConcept — relates an Opinion to the concept being predicated \n  of its subject (subproperty of dul:usesConcept)\n- prov:wasGeneratedBy — relates an Opinion to the prov:Activity that \n  produced it\n\nOther properties of DUL can also be used to further describe the Opinion \n(such as dul:introduces). The core ones (opino:isPremisedOn, \nopino:describes, opino:usesConcept) were instantiated into OPINO for \nclarity, as subproperties of their DUL counterparts scoped to \nopino:Opinion as domain.\n\nThe properties of a Construal are:\n- opino:grounds — relates a Construal to the Opinion it supports, as \n  premises support a conclusion (inverse of isPremisedOn; subproperty \n  of dul:satisfies)\n- opino:involves — relates a Construal to any entity — object, agent, \n  event, or abstract concept — that the cognizer perceives as \n  participating in the construed state of affairs (subproperty of \n  dul:isSettingFor). When a Construal satisfies a Framester frame via \n  dul:satisfies, the roles of the involved entities can be made explicit \n  using Framester frame element properties (e.g. fe:Artifact.forgery, \n  fe:Means.forgery), providing a more granular representation without \n  requiring modification of the core pattern.\n- opino:perceivedBy — relates a Construal to the cognizer whose \n  perspective constitutes it (range: owl:Thing; subproperty of \n  dul:associatedWith)\n- opino:hasPart — relates a Construal to its constituent sub-Construals, \n  each representing an individual premise (subproperty of dul:hasPart; \n  allValuesFrom opino:Construal)\n- opino:presupposes — relates a Construal to another Construal that must \n  hold as a logical or epistemic premise before it (subproperty of \n  dul:hasPrecondition)\n- opino:enables — relates a Construal to another Construal it makes \n  possible as a subsequent inferential step (subproperty of \n  dul:hasPostcondition)\n- dul:satisfies — optionally relates a sub-Construal to a dul:Description, \n  typically a Framester frame (Gangemi et al. 2016), providing the \n  conceptual vocabulary through which the construed state of affairs \n  is interpreted\n\nA Construal can be extended in two ways. First, by converting it into \na TimeIndexedConstrual — a subclass of opino:Construal equivalent to a \nConstrual that has at least one opino:holdsAtTime relation pointing to a \ndul:TimeInterval — for temporally bounded perceptions, such as 'yesterday \nMarco did something good' or 'this painting was attributed to Caravaggio \nduring the period 1990–2005'. Second, by decomposing it into \nsub-Construals via opino:hasPart, each of which may itself be satisfied \nby a Framester frame describing the inferential role of that premise \nwithin the overall construal. Sub-Construals can be ordered via \nopino:presupposes and opino:enables to represent the logical sequence \nof the inferential chain.\n\nOPINO is informed by the CRMinf extension of CIDOC CRM, the Digital \nHermeneutics model (Daquino, Pasqual and Tomasi 2021), and the SEBI \nontology (https://valentinapasqual.github.io/sebi/). It is released \nunder the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License \n(CC BY 4.0)"@en .
<http://w3id.org/opino/> <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/description> "OPINO is a content Ontology Design Pattern for representing scholarly interpretive opinions. It extends the Description and Situation (DnS) ODP by introducing epistemic status gradation, inter-opinion relations, and a provenance layer via PROV-O and HiCO. It is informed by the Digital Hermeneutics model (Daquino et al., 2021) and the SEBI ontology (https://valentinapasqual.github.io/sebi/)."@en .
<http://w3id.org/opino/> <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title> "OPINO - OPINion ONtology"@en .
<http://w3id.org/opino/> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "OPINO - OPINion ONtology"@en .
<http://w3id.org/opino/> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#versionInfo> "0.1.0" .
